<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-673-452  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 673 452.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  July 16 1990 n377 p101(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Banks 'tidy up' offices; toss paper, microfiche for opticalstorage.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Doyle, T.C.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Financial institutions are required by law to keep bankingtransaction records for seven years.andP;  Advanced imaging technologyand optical disk storage media enable banks, savings and loans andcredit unions to comply with these government regulations whileeliminating tons of paper files and microfiche.andP;  Permanentelectronic filing of records via such non-erasable storage mediaas WORMs has been approved by the courts.andP;  These techniques notonly save space but also improve efficiency and save money.andO;Western Bank of Oregon, for example, is replacing its microfichewith optical imaging systems based on microcomputers at a savingsof about $3,500 per month.andP;  First Interstate Bank is not yet usingoptical disk storage but is using imaging technology to replacesignature cards.andP;  Some banks hesitate to attempt optical storagebecause of a lack of technology to convert microfiche data tooptical format.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     BankingOptical DisksStorage MediaElectronic FilingWORMImaging Technology.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>